 {"id":"franken_networkx-zzcm9","title":"[HIGH] REVIEW: MultiGraph structural algorithms diverge from NetworkX","description":"The wide parity matrix found MultiGraph-specific structural gaps: is_tree and is_forest return true despite parallel edges where upstream returns false; bridges includes the parallel edge pair that upstream excludes; degree_centrality undercounts parallel-edge degree; complement raises TypeError where upstream returns a MultiGraph complement.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T00:56:26.319497097Z","created_by":"codex","updated_at":"2026-04-24T04:48:54.137026Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T04:48:54.137026Z","close_reason":"Fixed in cycle-continuation commit: Python overrides for is_tree/is_forest/bridges/degree_centrality/complement on MultiGraph input match nx contract (count parallels, exclude parallel-edge bridges, delegate complement to nx for MG).","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-edgesnone", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] G.edges(data=None, default=X) yields 2-tuples \u2014 nx centrality algos crash on fnx", "description": "nx contract: G.edges(data=None, default=X) yields 3-tuples where the third element is always `default` (not the attr value). The Rust EdgeView treated data=None the same as data=False and yielded 2-tuples. This broke nx internals in eigenvector_centrality_numpy / katz_centrality_numpy / resistance_distance / any algorithm that uses nx.to_scipy_sparse_array internally with weight=None, because they do `for u, v, wt in G.edges(data=weight, default=1)` and failed with ValueError: not enough values to unpack (expected 3, got 2). Fix in _edge_view_call_with_nbunch_first: detect data is None explicitly and append (default,) to each returned 2-tuple.", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T07:33:34.383606Z", "close_reason": "Fixed: data=None path in _edge_view_call_with_nbunch_first appends default to each edge tuple. 4 regression tests cover explicit data=None + end-to-end nx centrality algorithms on fnx.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T07:33:34.383606Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T07:33:34.383606Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-addedgesgen", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] add_edges_from(gen_that_reads_self) hits \"Already mutably borrowed\"", "description": "nx internals frequently do `G.add_edges_from(gen)` where gen reads G \u2014 e.g. nx.transitive_closure: `TC.add_edges_from((v, e[1]) for e in nx.edge_bfs(G, v) if e[1] not in TC[v])`. The Rust add_edges_from mutably borrows self's adjacency while iterating the ebunch; the generator's `TC[v]` read needs an immutable borrow on the same RefCell and raises `RuntimeError: Already mutably borrowed`. Fix: Python wrapper for Graph/DiGraph.add_edges_from materializes the ebunch into a list before handing it to Rust, so the generator fully evaluates (reading self) before any mutable borrow starts.", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T07:47:02.013671Z", "close_reason": "Fixed: _add_edges_from_materialized wraps Graph/DiGraph.add_edges_from to list() the ebunch first. 3 regression tests cover the nx.transitive_closure end-to-end case + the underlying mutably-borrowed pattern.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T07:47:02.013671Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T07:47:02.013671Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-adjkset", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] AdjacencyView.keys() returns plain iterator \u2014 breaks nx.non_neighbors set arithmetic", "description": "nx.non_neighbors does `graph._adj.keys() - graph._adj[node].keys() - {node}` expecting dict_keys-like views with set-operator support. fnx's _adjacency_view_keys returned a plain `iter(self)` generator, so the subtraction raised TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for -. This broke many nx algorithms that use non_neighbors internally, including approximation.clique_removal and ramsey.ramsey_R2. Fix: _adjacency_view_keys now returns a _AdjKeysView wrapping a collections.abc.KeysView around a list snapshot, so -, |, &, ^ all work.", "status": "closed", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T07:52:51.336735Z", "close_reason": "Fixed: _adjacency_view_keys returns a KeysView subclass with full set-operator support. Applied to AdjacencyView, MultiAdjacencyView, AtlasView, _GRAPH_ADJACENCY_VIEW_TYPE, _DIGRAPH_ADJACENCY_VIEW_TYPE, and EdgeView types.", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T07:52:51.336735Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T07:52:51.336735Z", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
